<TITLE> 3 deals expected from Thimphu </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 15 (bdnews24.com)The South Asian leaders will sign three regional agreements during the SAARC summit scheduled on April 28-29. Bhutanese ambassador Dasho Bap Kesang told reporters Thursday afternoon, that the summit would inaugurate the headquarters of SAARC Development Fund in Thimphu. He said the 17th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation may be held in Male next year. "We are very happy that the member countries have agreed to sign three deals." These would be a convention on cooperation on environment, agreement on trade in services and agreement on natural disaster rapid response mechanism in the region Kesang told reporters. Bhutan is hosting the SAARC summit for the first since founding of the regional body in Dhaka in 1985. The ambassador said his country was very happy for the selection of climate change as the central theme of the 17th SAARC summit. "Climate change will harm most of the member countries including Bangladesh," he said. The envoy said Bhutan was the only country to see expansion of greenery since 1960s. "In 1960s, Bhutan had 70 percent of its land with vegetation cover." Kesang said it had gone up to 72 percent now. He said the Bhutanese constitution of 2008 had inserted a section saying the country must have 60 percent greenery. "It is very crucial that climate change has been selected as the central theme," he said. He said the capital Thimphu was ready to host the summit. Heads of the eight member states or governments will deliver speeches on regional cooperation on April 28 and 29. The foreign ministers of Afghanistan, Bangladesh, India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka will meet on April 27. The eight foreign secretaries will sit on April 26 to finalise the summit's agenda. Formalities are set to kick off on April 24 with the meeting of directors general and directors of the foreign ministries of the member countries. The summit will adopt a declaration to
